   "source": [
    "### One-Hot Encoding\n",
    "One-hot encoding is a technique used to ensure that categorical variables are better represented in the machine. Let's take a look at the \"Sex\" column"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "zxl62Q0-9ay1",
    "outputId": "1b2e62ad-3707-424d-fc21-26d413fc9221"
   },
   "outputs": [

      ]

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "sXIAVO4Z9ay8"
   },
   "source": [
    "Machine Learning classifiers don't know how to handle strings. As a result, you need to convert it into a categorical representation. There are two main ways to go about this:\n",
    "\n",
    "Label Encoding: Assigning, for example, 0 for \"male\" and 1 for \"female\". The problem here is it intrinsically makes one category \"larger than\" the other category.\n",
    "\n",
    "One-hot encoding: Assigning, for example, [1, 0] for \"male\" and [0, 1] for female. In this case, you have an array of size (n_categories,) and you represent a 1 in the correct index, and 0 elsewhere. In Pandas, this would show as extra columns. For example, rather than having a \"Sex\" column, it would be a \"Sex_male\" and \"Sex_female\" column. Then, if the person is male, it would simply show as a 1 in the \"Sex_male\" column and a 0 in the \"Sex_female\" column.\n",
    "\n",
    "There is a nice and easy method that does this in pandas: get_dummies()"
   ]
  },

    "# Split the data into training, development, and test set\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "X = titanic_df.drop(\"Survived\", axis=1)\n",
    "y = titanic_df[\"Survived\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "# First split into training and development + test set\n",
    "X_train, X_devtest, y_train, y_devtest = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.4, random_state=42)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Then split the remaining development + test set into development and test set\n",
    "X_dev, X_test, y_dev, y_test = train_test_split(X_devtest, y_devtest, test_size=0.5, random_state=42)"
   ]
  },

    "# Train the Decision Tree using different max_depth(d) values\n",
    "train_accuracies = []\n",
    "dev_accuracies = []\n",
    "max_depths = range(2, 11)\n",
    "for max_depth in max_depths:\n",
    "    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=max_depth, random_state=42)\n",
    "    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "    train_accuracy = clf.score(X_train, y_train)\n",

    "# Accuracy lines plot\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "plt.plot(max_depths, train_accuracies, label=\"Train Accuracy\", marker=\"o\")\n",
    "plt.plot(max_depths, dev_accuracies, label=\"Development Accuracy\", marker=\"o\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Training vs Development Accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Decision Tree depth\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.grid(True)\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The accuracy curves show a case of overfitting, where the training accuracy increases with depth while the development accuracy remains relatively stable and flat and drops at higher depths. This indicates that the model is becoming too complex and is fitting noise in the training data rather than capturing the underlying patterns in the data. This imbalance suggests that as the depth of the decision tree increases, the model is fitting the training data too closely, leading to high training accuracy but poor generalization to the development set.\n",
    "\n",
    "The best tree depth is the one that balances high training accuracy with high development accuracy. In this case, it appears that a depth of 7 provides a good balance, as the training accuracy is high while the development accuracy remains relatively stable and does not drop significantly. Although depth of 8 continue to improve the training accuracy,it does not significantly improve generalization to the development set. Therefore, a depth of 7 is recommended as the best tree depth for this dataset as it gives the best balance between accuracy and generalization.\n"
   ]
  },

    "clf_final = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=7, random_state=42)\n",
    "clf_final.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "test_accuracy = clf_final.score(X_test, y_test)\n",
    "print(f\"The Test Set Accuracy of the Final Model is:{test_accuracy:.4f}\")"
   ]

    "The final decision tree model was trained with a maximum depth of 7. The model attained an accuracy of 0.7753 on previously unseen data. This is slightly lower than the development accuracy(0.8202),as expected, but it still demonstrates that the model generalizes effectively. Overall, the test accuracy indicates that the model can produce reasonably accurate predictions on new data and is not overfitting too much."
